## 2. Technology & Component Mapping

### 2.1 Kubernetes Distribution

| Environment | Distribution | Rationale |
|------------|-------------|-----------|
| **Local dev** | Minikube (latest) | Lightweight, single-node, supports Dapr + Helm; 4 CPU / 8GB RAM minimum |
| **Cloud (preferred)** | Oracle OKE Always Free | 4 ARM cores + 24GB RAM, $0 cost, permanent — covers all 6 pods |
| **Cloud (alternative)** | GKE Standard | Free control plane, $28/month for e2-small nodes; viable within $300 credit |
| **Cloud (alternative)** | AKS | Free control plane, ~$82/month — use only if Azure credits available |

### 2.2 Kafka / Redpanda Decision

| Environment | Kafka Implementation | Connection |
|------------|---------------------|-----------|
| **Minikube** | Strimzi Operator (self-hosted) | Internal K8s DNS: `kafka-cluster-kafka-bootstrap.kafka:9092` |
| **Cloud** | Redpanda Cloud Serverless (free tier) | External SASL/SSL endpoint via K8s secret |

**Rationale**: Strimzi is the only Kafka implementation that runs reliably on Minikube without
Zookeeper. Redpanda Cloud Serverless provides a free 10GB / 10MB/s tier that Dapr pubsub.kafka
connects to via SASL/SSL — zero code changes between environments (only Dapr component metadata
differs via `values.yaml` overrides).

### 2.3 Dapr Component Manifest Summary

| Component Name | Type | Key Metadata | Namespace Scope |
|---------------|------|-------------|----------------|
| `pubsub-kafka` | `pubsub.kafka` | `brokers`, `authType`, `saslUsername`, `saslPassword` (from secret) | `todo-app` |
| `state-postgresql` | `state.postgresql` | `connectionString` (from secret via secretstores.kubernetes) | `todo-app` |
| `secretstore-k8s` | `secretstores.kubernetes` | `vaultName: default` | `todo-app` |
| `dapr-jobs` | `jobs` (built-in) | Enabled via Dapr Scheduler service in control plane | `todo-app` |

All Dapr component manifests live under `charts/todo-app-v5/templates/dapr/`.

### 2.4 Database & External Services Mapping

| Service | External Dependency | Access Method | Secret Key |
|---------|--------------------|--------------|-----------:|
| Chat API | Neon PostgreSQL | SQLModel + asyncpg via `DATABASE_URL` | `todo-backend-secret` |
| Audit Service | Neon PostgreSQL | SQLModel (separate audit table) | `todo-backend-secret` |
| Recurring Service | Chat API (internal) | Dapr Service Invocation | none |
| Notification Service | (delivery stub for hackathon) | HTTP output or log-only | none |
| All services | Redpanda / Strimzi | Dapr pubsub.kafka via `pubsub-kafka` component | `kafka-secret` |

---

## 3. Event-Driven Backbone

### 3.1 Kafka Topic Configuration

| Topic | Partitions | Replication Factor | Retention |
|-------|-----------|-------------------|----------|
| `task-events` | 3 | 1 (Minikube) / 3 (cloud) | 7 days |
| `reminders` | 3 | 1 (Minikube) / 3 (cloud) | 3 days |
| `task-updates` | 3 | 1 (Minikube) / 3 (cloud) | 1 day |

Topics created automatically by Strimzi via `KafkaTopic` CRD (Minikube) or via Redpanda Cloud
console (cloud). Dapr pubsub.kafka will auto-create topics if `allowedTopics` is not restricted.

### 3.2 Producers and Consumers Per Topic

**topic: task-events**
| Direction | Service | Events |
|-----------|---------|--------|
| Producer | Chat API | `TaskCreated`, `TaskUpdated`, `TaskDeleted`, `TaskCompleted` |
| Consumer | Recurring Task Service | `TaskCompleted` (with recurrence field) |
| Consumer | Audit Service | All 4 event types |

**topic: reminders**
| Direction | Service | Events |
|-----------|---------|--------|
| Producer | Dapr Jobs API (via Scheduler → Chat API handler) | `ReminderScheduled`, `ReminderFired` |
| Consumer | Notification Service | `ReminderFired` |
| Consumer | Audit Service | `ReminderScheduled`, `ReminderFired` |

**topic: task-updates**
| Direction | Service | Events |
|-----------|---------|--------|
| Producer | Chat API | `TaskSyncUpdate` (created/updated/deleted/completed) |
| Consumer | WebSocket Service | `TaskSyncUpdate` → broadcast to all WS clients |

### 3.3 Event Schema References

All event schemas are defined in `speckit.event-schemas.json` at repo root (generated by
`/speckit-event-schema-validation`). Key schemas:

| Event | Schema Version | Idempotency Key | Backward Compatible |
|-------|---------------|----------------|---------------------|
| `TaskCreated` | 1.0.0 | `event_id` (UUID) | ✅ BACKWARD |
| `TaskUpdated` | 1.0.0 | `event_id` (UUID) | ✅ BACKWARD |
| `TaskDeleted` | 1.0.0 | `event_id` (UUID) | ✅ BACKWARD |
| `TaskCompleted` | 1.0.0 | `event_id` (UUID) | ✅ BACKWARD |
| `ReminderScheduled` | 1.0.0 | `event_id` (UUID) | ✅ BACKWARD |
| `ReminderFired` | 1.0.0 | `event_id` (UUID) | ✅ BACKWARD |
| `TaskSyncUpdate` | 1.0.0 | `event_id` (UUID) | ✅ BACKWARD |

All events carry: `event_id`, `event_type`, `schema_version`, `timestamp` (ISO 8601), `task_id`, `user_id`.

### 3.4 Publish / Consume Pattern (Dapr Pub/Sub Only)

**Publishing** (Chat API → Dapr sidecar):
```
POST http://localhost:3500/v1.0/publish/pubsub-kafka/task-events
Body: { event_id, event_type, schema_version, timestamp, task_id, user_id, ... }
```

**Subscribing** (Consumer service → Dapr subscription):
```
Dapr subscription route: POST /task-events-handler
Dapr declarative subscription YAML in charts/todo-app-v5/templates/dapr/subscriptions.yaml
```

**Idempotency enforcement**: Every consumer MUST check a dedup table in PostgreSQL keyed on
`event_id` before processing. On duplicate, return HTTP 200 immediately without side effects.

---

## 4. Scheduling & Reminder / Recurring Logic

### 4.1 Why Dapr Jobs API Over Cron

| Approach | Problem | Dapr Jobs API Advantage |
|----------|---------|------------------------|
| Cron binding | Fires on interval, not at exact time — requires poll + check | Fires at exact UTC timestamp with sub-second precision |
| Polling loop | Blocks async event loop; wastes resources | No polling — scheduler calls back exactly once |
| APScheduler | Python-only; doesn't survive pod restarts without state | Jobs API persists in Dapr Scheduler service — survives restarts |
| Kubernetes CronJob | Minute-level granularity only | Jobs API supports ISO 8601 with second-level precision |

### 4.2 Reminder Scheduling Flow

```
POST /tasks  →  Chat API
    │
    ├─ [due_date present?] YES
    │       │
    │       ▼
    │   POST http://localhost:3500/v1.0/jobs/reminder-{task_id}
    │   Body: { dueTime: "<ISO8601>", data: { task_id, user_id, title } }
    │
    │   Dapr Scheduler stores job in etcd-backed store
    │
    │   [At exact due_date moment]
    │       │
    │       ▼
    │   Dapr Scheduler → POST /job/reminder-{task_id}  →  Chat API job handler
    │                                                        │
    │                                                        ▼
    │                                               Publishes ReminderFired
    │                                               to `reminders` topic
    │
    └─ Always: publish TaskCreated to task-events
```

**Job naming convention**: `reminder-{task_id}` — ensures one job per task, supports cancellation
on task deletion via `DELETE http://localhost:3500/v1.0/jobs/reminder-{task_id}`.

### 4.3 Recurring Task Spawn Flow

```
PATCH /tasks/{id}/complete  →  Chat API
    │
    ├─ Publishes TaskCompleted to task-events
    │       │
    │       ▼
    │   Recurring Task Service (subscribes to task-events)
    │       │
    │       ├─ [recurrence present?] YES
    │       │       │
    │       │       ▼
    │       │   Calculate next_due from recurrence.interval + recurrence.every
    │       │   (daily → +1 day, weekly → +7 days, monthly → +1 month, custom → +N days)
    │       │       │
    │       │       ▼
    │       │   Dapr Service Invocation:
    │       │   POST http://localhost:3500/v1.0/invoke/todo-backend/method/internal/tasks
    │       │   Body: { title, due_date: next_due, recurrence, user_id, priority, tags }
    │       │       │
    │       │       ▼
    │       │   Chat API creates new task → publishes TaskCreated
    │       │
    │       └─ [recurrence absent?] SKIP — no action
    │
    └─ Audit Service independently logs TaskCompleted
```

---

## 5. State & Secrets Management

### 5.1 Dapr State Store Configuration (PostgreSQL + Neon)

**Component**: `state.postgresql`
**Purpose**: Store conversation context per user session; short-lived task cache for MCP responses.

State key pattern:
```
conversation:{user_id}:{session_id}   → JSON: last N messages, active task context
task-cache:{task_id}                  → JSON: task snapshot (TTL: 5 minutes)
```

**Dapr state operations** (all via sidecar HTTP, never direct DB):
```
GET    http://localhost:3500/v1.0/state/state-postgresql/{key}
POST   http://localhost:3500/v1.0/state/state-postgresql  Body: [{key, value, options}]
DELETE http://localhost:3500/v1.0/state/state-postgresql/{key}
```

Connection string supplied via Dapr secretstore — never in component YAML directly.

### 5.2 Secrets Strategy — Kubernetes SecretStore

**Dapr Component**: `secretstores.kubernetes`
All secrets are created imperatively (never in Helm values or source code) before `helm install`:

```
kubectl create secret generic todo-backend-secret \
  --from-literal=DATABASE_URL=postgresql+asyncpg://... \
  --from-literal=OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-... \
  --from-literal=BETTER_AUTH_SECRET=... \
  -n todo-app

kubectl create secret generic kafka-secret \
  --from-literal=KAFKA_BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS=<redpanda-or-strimzi-endpoint> \
  --from-literal=KAFKA_API_KEY=<redpanda-sasl-user> \
  --from-literal=KAFKA_API_SECRET=<redpanda-sasl-password> \
  -n todo-app
```

Services read secrets via Dapr at startup:
```
GET http://localhost:3500/v1.0/secrets/secretstore-k8s/todo-backend-secret
```

**Secret rotation**: No pod restart needed — Dapr refreshes secret cache on next read cycle.

### 5.3 Security Invariants

- No secret field in any `values.yaml`, `configmap.yaml`, or source file.
- All Dapr component manifests reference secrets via `secretKeyRef` — not literal values.
- NetworkPolicy restricts cross-namespace traffic: only `todo-app` → `dapr-system` allowed.

---

## 6. Service-to-Service & Frontend-Backend Communication

### 6.1 Dapr Service Invocation Usage

The only internal synchronous call in Phase V is Recurring Task Service → Chat API:

```
Dapr Service Invocation:
  Source: recurring-service (Dapr app-id: recurring-service)
  Target: todo-backend   (Dapr app-id: todo-backend)
  Method: POST /internal/tasks
  Via:    http://localhost:3500/v1.0/invoke/todo-backend/method/internal/tasks

Dapr handles: mTLS, retries, load balancing, service discovery
```

The `/internal/tasks` endpoint is **not exposed externally** — protected by NetworkPolicy and
Dapr's service invocation mTLS enforcement.

### 6.2 Frontend → Backend Pattern

```
Browser (Next.js App Router)
    │
    ├─ API Routes (server-side) → fetch("http://todo-backend-svc:8000/...")
    │   Used for: auth, task CRUD, chat completions
    │
    └─ WebSocket Client → ws://websocket-service-svc:8001/ws/tasks
        Used for: real-time task updates pushed from WebSocket Service
```

Frontend communicates with backend exclusively through:
- Server-side API routes (avoids CORS; keeps API key server-side)
- WebSocket connection to WebSocket Service for live updates

### 6.3 Port Allocation

| Service | Internal Port | Dapr HTTP | Dapr gRPC |
|---------|-------------|----------|----------|
| todo-backend | 8000 | 3500 | 50001 |
| todo-frontend | 3000 | 3500 | 50001 |
| recurring-service | 8001 | 3500 | 50001 |
| notification-service | 8002 | 3500 | 50001 |
| audit-service | 8003 | 3500 | 50001 |
| websocket-service | 8004 | 3500 | 50001 |

Each pod has its own Dapr sidecar on port 3500 (localhost) — no cross-pod port conflicts.

---

## 7. Deployment Sequencing

### Part A: Prerequisites (Both Environments)

Before any deployment, the following MUST be complete:
1. Neon PostgreSQL database provisioned and connection string available.
2. Alembic migrations run against Neon (`alembic upgrade head`).
3. All Docker images built and tagged: `todo-backend`, `todo-frontend`, `recurring-service`, `notification-service`, `audit-service`, `websocket-service`.

---

### Part B: Minikube Local Deployment Sequence

```
Step 1: Start Minikube with sufficient resources
  minikube start --cpus=4 --memory=8192 --disk-size=40g

Step 2: Enable Minikube addons
  minikube addons enable ingress
  minikube addons enable metrics-server

Step 3: Install Dapr CLI + Control Plane
  dapr init -k --wait
  # Verify: dapr status -k → all components Running

Step 4: Deploy Strimzi Kafka Operator
  kubectl create namespace kafka
  kubectl apply -f https://strimzi.io/install/latest?namespace=kafka -n kafka
  # Wait for operator: kubectl rollout status deployment/strimzi-cluster-operator -n kafka

Step 5: Deploy Strimzi Kafka Cluster
  kubectl apply -f charts/todo-app-v5/templates/kafka/strimzi-cluster.yaml -n kafka
  # Wait: kubectl wait kafka/kafka-cluster --for=condition=Ready --timeout=300s -n kafka

Step 6: Create K8s Secrets (imperative — not in Helm)
  kubectl create namespace todo-app
  kubectl create secret generic todo-backend-secret \
    --from-literal=DATABASE_URL=<neon-url> \
    --from-literal=OPENAI_API_KEY=<key> \
    --from-literal=BETTER_AUTH_SECRET=<secret> -n todo-app
  kubectl create secret generic kafka-secret \
    --from-literal=KAFKA_BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS=kafka-cluster-kafka-bootstrap.kafka:9092 \
    -n todo-app

Step 7: Load Docker images into Minikube
  minikube image load todo-backend:latest
  minikube image load todo-frontend:latest
  minikube image load recurring-service:latest
  minikube image load notification-service:latest
  minikube image load audit-service:latest
  minikube image load websocket-service:latest

Step 8: Helm install todo-app-v5
  helm install todo-chatbot-v5 ./charts/todo-app-v5 \
    -f charts/todo-app-v5/values.yaml \
    -n todo-app

Step 9: Verify all pods Running with Dapr sidecar (2/2)
  kubectl get pods -n todo-app
  # Expected: 6 pods, each showing 2/2 READY

Step 10: Verify Dapr components
  kubectl get components -n todo-app
  # Expected: pubsub-kafka, state-postgresql, secretstore-k8s → all Ready

Step 11: Port-forward for local access (or use minikube service)
  minikube service todo-frontend-svc -n todo-app --url
```

---

### Part C: Oracle OKE Cloud Deployment Sequence

```
Step 1: Create OKE cluster (Quick Create via OCI console)
  - Choose: ARM shape A1.Flex, 4 OCPU, 24GB RAM
  - Node pool: 2 worker nodes (Always Free)
  - VCN: Quick Create (auto-provisions subnets, IGW, security lists)
  - K8s version: 1.30.x (latest)

Step 2: Configure kubectl context
  oci ce cluster create-kubeconfig --cluster-id <ocid> \
    --file $HOME/.kube/config --region <region> --token-version 2.0.0
  kubectl get nodes   # Verify nodes Ready

Step 3: Install Dapr on OKE
  dapr init -k --wait
  dapr status -k   # All components healthy

Step 4: Create namespace and K8s secrets
  kubectl create namespace todo-app
  kubectl create secret generic todo-backend-secret \
    --from-literal=DATABASE_URL=<neon-url> \
    --from-literal=OPENAI_API_KEY=<key> \
    --from-literal=BETTER_AUTH_SECRET=<secret> -n todo-app
  kubectl create secret generic kafka-secret \
    --from-literal=KAFKA_BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS=<redpanda-cloud-endpoint> \
    --from-literal=KAFKA_API_KEY=<sasl-user> \
    --from-literal=KAFKA_API_SECRET=<sasl-password> -n todo-app

Step 5: Configure Redpanda Cloud (external managed Kafka)
  - Log in to Redpanda Cloud (cloud.redpanda.com)
  - Create Serverless cluster
  - Create topics: task-events, reminders, task-updates (3 partitions each)
  - Create SASL user; note bootstrap server + credentials

Step 6: Helm install with cloud values overlay
  helm install todo-chatbot-v5 ./charts/todo-app-v5 \
    -f charts/todo-app-v5/values.yaml \
    -f charts/todo-app-v5/values.cloud.yaml \
    -f charts/todo-app-v5/values.redpanda.yaml \
    -n todo-app

  # values.cloud.yaml overrides: imagePullPolicy=Always, Ingress enabled, replicas
  # values.redpanda.yaml overrides: Dapr pubsub-kafka brokers + SASL config

Step 7: Verify cloud deployment
  kubectl get pods -n todo-app          # All 6 pods 2/2 Ready
  kubectl get components -n todo-app    # All Dapr components Ready
  kubectl get ingress -n todo-app       # External IP assigned
```

**OKE ARM64 note**: All Docker images MUST be built for `linux/arm64` (or multi-arch).
Use GitHub Actions matrix: `platforms: linux/amd64,linux/arm64` in buildx step.

---

### Part D: CI/CD GitHub Actions Pipeline

```
Trigger: push to main branch

Job 1: lint-test (parallel matrix)
  - backend: pytest backend/tests/ -v --cov=backend
  - frontend: npm test (jest)
  - helm: helm lint charts/todo-app-v5/

Job 2: build-push (requires lint-test pass)
  Matrix: [todo-backend, todo-frontend, recurring-service,
           notification-service, audit-service, websocket-service]
  Steps:
    - docker/setup-buildx-action
    - docker/build-push-action
      platforms: linux/amd64,linux/arm64
      tags: ghcr.io/${{ github.repository }}/<service>:${{ github.sha }}
      push: true

Job 3: deploy-staging (requires build-push)
  Steps:
    - Configure kubectl (OIDC or kubeconfig secret)
    - helm upgrade --install todo-chatbot-v5 ./charts/todo-app-v5 \
        -f values.cloud.yaml -f values.redpanda.yaml \
        --set global.imageTag=${{ github.sha }} -n todo-app

Job 4: smoke-test (requires deploy-staging)
  Steps:
    - kubectl rollout status deployment/todo-backend -n todo-app --timeout=120s
    - curl health check against external Ingress URL

Job 5: deploy-production (requires smoke-test + manual approval gate)
  environment: production   # GitHub environment with required reviewers
  Steps:
    - helm upgrade todo-chatbot-v5 ... (production values)
```

---

## 8. Monitoring, Logging & Observability

### 8.1 Baseline (Phase V Required)

| Tool | Command | Purpose |
|------|---------|---------|
| `kubectl logs` | `kubectl logs -l app=todo-backend -n todo-app --follow` | Service stdout/stderr |
| Dapr logs | `kubectl logs -l app=todo-backend -c daprd -n todo-app` | Sidecar pub/sub events, state ops |
| `kubectl describe pod` | `kubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n todo-app` | Probe failures, OOM events |
| `dapr dashboard` | `dapr dashboard -k` | Visual component status and service graph |
| Dapr metrics endpoint | `http://localhost:9090/metrics` (sidecar) | Prometheus-compatible scrape |

### 8.2 Structured Logging Pattern

All FastAPI services MUST use structured JSON logging:
```python
import structlog
log = structlog.get_logger()
log.info("task_created", task_id=str(task.id), user_id=str(user.id), event_id=str(event_id))
```

Log levels: `INFO` for business events, `ERROR` for failures, `DEBUG` for Dapr round-trips (disabled in production).

### 8.3 Future Observability Additions (Post-Phase V)

| Addition | Tool | Trigger |
|----------|------|---------|
| Metrics scraping | Prometheus + Grafana (Helm chart) | When >5 users |
| Distributed tracing | Dapr Zipkin component | When debugging cross-service latency |
| Alerting | Alertmanager → Slack webhook | When deploying to production |
| Log aggregation | Grafana Loki | When log volume exceeds kubectl capacity |

